movements","Plans complex sequential movements"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Econtrol of axial muscle movements and balance\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of the cerebellar vermis. Located in the midline of the cerebellum, the vermis receives extensive input from vestibular nuclei and the spinal cord to coordinate postural muscles and maintain equilibrium.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoordination of fine finger movements\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily a function of the lateral cerebellar hemispheres\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcessing cognitive and emotional responses\u003C/strong\u003E - While the cerebellum has some role in emotion, this is not a primary function of the vermis\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlanning complex sequential movements\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily performed by motor planning areas in the cerebral cortex\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegulating speech production\u003C/strong\u003E - While the cerebellum contributes to speech coordination, this is not the primary function of the vermis\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EDamage to the vermis typically results in truncal ataxia, causing difficulties with balance and walking in a straight line. Patients often demonstrate a wide-based gait and may fall when attempting to stand still with their feet together.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The cerebellar vermis coordinates axial muscle movements and maintains trunk stability and balance.","The vermis receives input primarily from the vestibular system and spinal cord regarding posture and equilibrium.","Damage to the vermis results in truncal ataxia and difficulties with balance while standing or walking."],"references":["Coffman KA, Dum RP, Strick PL. Cerebellar vermis is a target of projections from the motor areas in the cerebral cortex. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2011 Sep 20;108(38):16068-73. doi: 10.1073/pnas.1107904108. Epub 2011 Sep 12. PMID: 21911381; PMCID: PMC3179064.","Bledsoe J, Semrud-Clikeman M, Pliszka SR. A magnetic resonance imaging study of the cerebellar vermis in chronically treated and treatment-na\u00efve children with attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder combined type. Biol Psychiatry. 2009 Apr 1;65(7):620-4. doi: 10.1016/j.biopsych.2008.11.030. Epub 2009 Jan 15. PMID: 19150052; PMCID: PMC2675536.","Unverdi M, Alsayouri K. Neuroanatomy, Cerebellar Dysfunction. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545251/","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51052"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16537"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51052"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T16:07:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T11:54:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9228"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65613"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCoun